  <main class="content">

    <p class="intro-text">
      St Francis Girls Suwerwa is a co-educational school located in Suwerwa, Trans Nzoia County, Kenya, 
      with a rich and inspiring history. Founded in 1979 as a mixed boarding school by the late 
      President Daniel arap Moi  one of Kenya's longest-serving leaders  the school was named 
      after the nearby Kabarak Farm owned by President Moi. What began as a small institution 
      with a vision to serve Kenya's youth has grown into one of the country's most celebrated schools.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section-heading">A Journey Through Time</h2>

    <!-- TIMELINE -->
    <div class="timeline">

      <!-- 1979 -->
      <div class="timeline-item featured">
        <div class="timeline-year">1979</div>
        <div class="timeline-card">
          <h3>The Founding of SFGS</h3>
          <p>
            St Francis Girls Suwerwa was established as a mixed boarding school by the Late President 
            Daniel arap Moi, one of Kenya's longest-serving leaders. Named after the nearby Kabarak 
            Farm, the school opened its doors with a small student population and a small but dedicated 
            teaching staff  and a powerful vision: to provide affordable, quality education to Kenyan 
            children and prepare them for college and life.
          </p>
          <span class="tag"> Foundation</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Early Years -->
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">1980s</div>
        <div class="timeline-card">
          <h3>Growing Reputation</h3>
          <p>
            In its early years, the school built a steady reputation for academic discipline and 
            Christian values. Student numbers grew as word spread across Kenya of the school's 
            commitment to holistic education. The school's close proximity to Kabarak Farm gave 
            it a unique identity tied to national leadership and vision.
          </p>
          <span class="tag"> Growth</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 1990s -->
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">1990s</div>
        <div class="timeline-card">
          <h3>Expansion: Primary School & Kindergarten</h3>
          <p>
            A landmark decade of expansion: SFGS introduced a primary school section, followed 
            later by a kindergarten. The primary school has since become a key feeder institution 
            into the high school. A new, forward-looking curriculum was also introduced, emphasising 
            holistic education aimed at producing well-rounded students with strong leadership skills.
          </p>
          <span class="tag"> Expansion</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 2002 -->
      <div class="timeline-item featured">
        <div class="timeline-year">2002</div>
        <div class="timeline-card">
          <h3>A New Era: Board of Governors</h3>
          <p>
            A pivotal turning point in the school's history. Following President Moi's retirement 
            from politics, management of the school was handed over to a Board of Governors. 
            Simultaneously, the school began registering students directly with the Ministry of 
            Education  marking the end of an era as a purely private institution and the beginning 
            of a new chapter of wider public accountability.
          </p>
          <span class="tag"> Transition</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- International Recognition -->
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2000s2010s</div>
        <div class="timeline-card">
          <h3>International Academic Excellence</h3>
          <p>
            SFGS established itself on the world stage, sending students to represent Kenya in 
            prestigious international competitions including the World Scholar's Cup, the 
            International Mathematical Olympiad, and the International Physics Olympiad. 
            Academic and sporting achievements at both national and international levels cemented 
            the school's status as one of Kenya's finest.
          </p>
          <span class="tag"> International Recognition</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Alumni Legacy -->
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">Ongoing</div>
        <div class="timeline-card">
          <h3>A Legacy of Notable Alumni</h3>
          <p>
            Over the decades, SFGS has produced a large number of successful graduates who have 
            gone on to excel in medicine, politics, business, education, and many other fields. 
            The school's culture of fostering leadership, innovation, and entrepreneurship has 
            created an alumni network that is highly respected across Kenya and beyond  providing 
            mentorship and networking opportunities for current students.
          </p>
          <span class="tag"> Alumni Legacy</span>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div><!-- /timeline -->

    <!-- TODAY BOX -->
    <div class="today-box" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
      <h3>SFGS Today</h3>
      <p>
        St Francis Girls Suwerwa today stands as a thriving institution with over 2,000 students, 
        both male and female, offering a wide range of academic programs and extracurricular 
        activities including sports, music, and drama. Despite significant changes over the 
        decades, the school's core commitment  to provide affordable, holistic, Christian-based 
        education that produces well-rounded individuals  has never wavered.
      </p>
      <div class="today-highlights">
        <div class="highlight-chip">
          <strong>Students</strong>
          Over 2,000 enrolled
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-chip">
